Suppose you are given a time series of risk-factor returns. You carry out the exploratory procedures and tests described in this chapter. Which of the following is a true statement?


#not A significant Ljung-Box test implies that the data are heavier-tailed than normal.
#not An insignificant Ljung-Box implies that the time series can be assumed to be independent.
#not A Q-Q plot of the waiting times between the most extreme values against a normal distribution can reveal evidence of volatility.

#yes When volatility is present in a time series we can predict the magnitude of future returns.
This statement about volatility is true.


#not When volatility is present in a time series we can predict the direction of future returns.

